enance of settler identities, and then investigates how the British state and its allies brought an end to the reign of freelance, settler imperialism on the China coast. At the same time, other British sectors, missionary and business, renegotiated their own relationship with their Chinese markets and the Chinese state and distanced themselves from the settler British.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aImperialism. 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh  aBritain-in-China.  aBritish community.  aBritish diplomatic support.  aBritish imperialism.  aBritons.  aChina coast.  aChinese nationalism.  aPacific War.  aarchival materials.  abusinessmen.  adiplomats.  aimperial Britain.  ainter-war dissolution.  amass nationalism.  amilitant state.  amissionaries.  areign of freelance.  asettler communities.  asettlers.  atraders.1 aBickers, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611960540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526119605423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526119605/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles